And the wall collapsed ...
Here's a quiz for history enthusiasts: 20 years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4.
Which one do you remember best and which had the most significant consequences for the planet?
a) The bloody crackdown at Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few respond with c).
Because the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc during the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and therefore to the reformation of the post-war international order.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was an hour of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins are unknown.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement for change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader at the head of Poland, General Jaruzelski, judged that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to face alone.
Why not turn to the Polish opposition, he said - if not to find a solution, at least to share the responsibility for the situation with them?
After six months of negotiations, he reached a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections and Solidarnosc would be allowed to participate.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarnosc) ever considered for a single moment that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they didn't imagine they would be driven from power.
Yet, that is what happened.
In retrospect, it is surprising that there could have been doubts.
Solidarnosc ran a bold campaign.
A famous poster, repurposed for the occasion, that of a classic western film, "The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance," enjoyed great success: it shows a Gary Cooper holding a ballot instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4 was the day of judgment.
On this bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving birth to summer, voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to a final perversity that turned into an unintentional self-humiliation.
They devised an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting their preferred candidates, had to cross out the names of those they did not want—that is to say, all the communists listed on the ballots.
 Everywhere one looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had long been waiting for, the revenge on December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarnosc, and threw its leaders into prison.
The revolution by the pen!
Wielded with style, the pen that ultimately triumphs over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Some voters even tore up their ballots, thus decapitating the old regime with an effective stroke.
Others savored the moment, perhaps lighting a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "Look, this apparatchik got rich on our shortages," Pfft!
Pfft!
On the contrary, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
Across all of Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most relied on the media monopoly they had to get their message across: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist."
It can be said to its credit that the regime acknowledged its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the party's main officials and told them: "Our defeat is total," a political solution must be found."
It thus signified that he wanted neither violence nor fraud, the communists would have to live with the election result.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe knew that Solidarnosc was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would set an example for the rest of the Eastern Bloc.
The election in Poland was extremely encouraging for anticommunists around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what had seemed impossible just a few days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began tearing down the fences erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European Home" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously acknowledged: "We saw nothing coming."
The Cold War had lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom erupted.
